annotations: I’m broken

Angel is in pieces. She has freed herself, but now is faced with the task of rebuilding herself after her break up.

The break up in question could be a break up with her past self, the version of her that clung to the old cell that she thought kept her safe.

Angel came out in 2021 as a lesbian, and she may be referencing her journey of self acceptance and living a life that honours her authentic self, as that would require letting go of (i.e., breaking up with) who she thought she was before.

PROPOSED SUGGESTION: is she rebuilding herself after a break up or after leaving that old cell (coming out, accepting her sexuality etc)?

Here it comes
 No way to stop it now
 I’m broken
 Down for you like no one else
 Like no one else

Angel is preparing for the inevitable break up/escape. There is no way to stop the trajectory of this circumstance.

Angel acknowledges that she was broken down from this situation, and that she has given up much of herself for this person, hinting at a deeply intimate relationship (“for you, like no one else”).

But nothing’s free
 Like breaking free

Nothing is free, even the act of becoming free. Especially in terms of coming out – freedom of authentic self expression is gained, but many other things change, such as being at risk of homophobic discrimination and possible rejection from loved ones.

Additionally, leaving a situation that is no longer good for you (especially when it’s been your safe haven, to the point of your own detriment by inhibiting personal growth) requires the payment of “giving up” the part of you that desires to cling to that familiar situation. Angel is at the precipice of personal growth, and makes an exchange to move forward.

Here it comes
 Feel it break
 That old cell
 The one you thought had kept you safe

Angel is describing a transitional period – she is  leaving a situation/place, one that she had mistakenly believed to be a safe haven.

Angel might be referencing her coming out in 2021, and breaking free of being in the closet (“that old cell”) and finally living her as her authentic self. It can feel safer in the closet (and some people are forced to stay closeted for many reasons, especially for physical safety) but it seems like Angel came to the personal realization that being out was worth more than the safety that  she gained from passing as a straight woman.

It’s also possible that she is discussing a relationship that initially was a place of comfort and refuge, but eventually became restrictive and isolating (in other words, something or someone she ultimately had to break free from).

Out of the past these chains I know
 I’ll never be more sure of anything

Angel is confident that she’ll never view the ending of this situation as anything other than an advocation for her own freedom. Despite everything, this is an escape for freedom (“out of these past chains”).

PROPOSED SUGGESTION: These chains might be related to her inability to let go of the past, or being closeted. Her coming out was her finally breaking the chains.

description.plain:
“Shut Up Kiss Me”, the second single to be released in advance of Angel Olsen’s third studio LP My Woman, is an electric guitar-driven song in the vein of previous tracks “Forgiven/Forgotten” and “Hi-Five”.

It also serves a nice contrast to the synth-laced crooning of the other advance single “Intern” while showcasing Olsen’s vocals and guitar playing as even more relentless and defiant than in the purest rock tracks of her previous album, but nevertheless maintaining and expanding of her recurrent subjects: the fallout of a relationship, the difficulties in properly communicating with a lover, and the need for affection and connection despite all the hardships that come attached to it.

“Shut Up Kiss Me” works as a plea to a love interest in hopes that they’ll respect her and reconsider giving the relationship a second shot, but it also serves as a confident showcase of a woman’s courage to speak her mind in pursuit of her goals (whatever those may be). Olsen may “still [be] young”, but she seems to be getting more and more resolute in making sure the world takes notice of her. And so we should.

annotations:
I could make it all go away
 Tell me what you’re thinking, don’t delay
 We could still be having some sweet memories
 This heart still beats for you, why can’t you see?

Olsen believes that she alone has the ability to solve the problems in the relationship. Often this desire to fix someone results in toxic codependency as you look at what the relationship could be or could have been. She still loves this person despite their stubbornness and in the chorus expresses her need to be consoled.

I could make it all disappear
 You could feed me all of your fears
 We could end all this pain right here
 We could rewind all of those tears
 I could take it down to the floor
 You don’t have to feel it anymore
 A love so real that it can’t be ignored
 It’s all over, baby blue, I’m still yours
 I’m still yours

She offers her lover to put all of their troubles and fears onto her. She is willing to carry this load. Perhaps she hopes that if she can absorb her lover’s pain she can save the relationship from its demise. These very straight-forward lines deal with overcoming adversities by means of their attachment and mutual nurturing.

The last line may be a reference to Bob Dylan’s “It’s All Over Now, Baby Blue.” While in Dylan’s song it is an enigmatic phrase, with its most prominent meaning being about death and finding peace in it, here she twists the phrase to mean the end of the feelings which caused this song, the lack of communication and the constant arguing of the couple depicted.

While unlikely, this reference may hint to the fact that she believes this relationship can not be sustained without the constant fighting.

I ain’t hanging up this time
 I ain’t giving up tonight
 Even if you walk around as though you think you’re right
 At your worst, I still believe it’s worth the fight
She refuses to drop the relationship due to a disagreement, because she knows, at the end of the day, it’s worth more than that. The “fight” is just misdirected passion.

body.plain:
“Some Things Cosmic” is the fifth track from Angel Olsen’s debut EP, Strange Cacti.

The song serves as the poetic introduction for Olsen, with simple metaphors masking the deeper, more contemplative meaning.

annotations: I’m floating away

Floating way implies the inevitability of being without someone. Whether this “You” is a romantic or platonic figure, all people separate. If not by choice, by death. Floating away is inevitable, but the speaker makes a point to say that when the day of separation comes, they are taking with them all of the lessons and love they obtained in the relationship. The song is a touching lament for being without someone you love deeply.
Know that I’m hanging on to the things that you said

The speaker is deeply changed by the relationship they’ve had with the beloved “you.” The things said could be good or bad, but when the absence of someone you love occurs, people tend to cling to the memories and conversations.

If we should part, my dear dear love
 You know you’re in my heart

The “if” impiles that they might part but they might as well don’t. They might be physically separated, but they won’t be mentally: they would still be in each other’s hearts even if the “cosmic force” makes them split.
It’s something that doesen’t have an explanation, it just is- like their relationship.
“Love” itself hasn’t an explanation either: as the title says, some things are cosmic.
Know that I’m going with you
Even if the two are leaving, part of them are still in the other’s one mind. The universe and the cosmic force that makes it revolve may have separate them, but they’re mentally still by their side.

I want to be naked
 I don’t mean my body

This implies a non-sexual connection between the two, that something other that physical makes them gravitate near each other.
While a sexual attraction is easilly explained a mental or a platonic connection is difficult to tell: some things are cosmic, impossible to explain and without a real reason. Some thing just are, and because of the force that pushes them together are meant to be.
I’m floating away

The whole song revolves about the idea of a force that unites and draws away every part of the universe.
Now, when she says she’s floating away, that might mean that the same force that pushed her near the other person is now making her floating away from them into the cosmic stream force.

If cosmic force is real at all
 It’s come between you and I

Cosmic force is a certain belief in both pop culture and religion that can be taken in many different ways. In this case, Olsen is likely referring to the idea that there is a “supreme being”, or a certain system of thought that doesn’t assume the form of a singular deity or God.

The term “cosmic force” is also used to describe a concept developed by Greek philosopher Aristotle, called an “unmoved mover”. The idea behind the unmoved mover is that it is the primary force that causes the motion of the universe.

annotations: I have to look out too

What I believe she means by this is that she has to keep one foot out of the relationship to keep her purpose and sanity by balancing her feelings for her partner. It’s like putting all of your eggs in one basket. If it were to fall apart then a sense of purpose will be cracked because you put all of your purpose in life into the hands of your partner.
Here’s to thinking that it all meant so much more
she realises this relationship isn’t working and so she lets them leave and must now begin to find herself again back to before she met them
I started dancing just to be around you
she began to center her life around her lover just to be with them as much as possible, consequently leading to her losing herself in this other person
If all the trouble in my heart would only mend

she doesn’t want to be in pain anymore. she doesn’t want to feel like the end is the only answer to how she feels. she knows that she needs to push through this pain because she has to ‘save her life'
I wanted nothing but for this to be the end

this line can be interpreted in many ways: one of them being the obvious which is the end of the relationship she introduces in the first three lines but i personally think it can also mean the end of everything, ending her life. for so long this relationship gave her purpose and now she feels she’s lost it again because she’s lost this person and therefore needs to find her own reason to live again to avoid her urges
I quit my dreaming the moment that I found you
when she meets said person she feels so happy and fulfilled that she no longer needs to dream to escape reality
I lost my dream, I lost my reason all again
In the end she lost everything she wanted for herself when she wasn’t with him, she therefore lost her reason and arguably sanity
I kept my mouth shut and opened up the door
She silence her opinions and expression of certain emotions to him, so much so that she even forgot what she believed. She loved him so much so- that she kept her heart and commitment fully to him.

You may not be around
 You may not be around
 You may not be around
The repetitive language of these three stanzas serve as a mantra for her to move on with her life now that the person she is singing about is no longer in her life.

I am the only one now
 I am the only one now
 I am the only one now
 I am the only one now

Again, this is part of her mantra to move on. The cyclical sound of the chords reflect her entering a trance like state as she tries to help herself find “peace of mind”. These lines have both positive and negative connotations; she is “the only one now” and thereby able to find strength in moving on with her life, but is also faced with the task of ‘unfucking’ the world on her own. These lines could also refer to her being trapped in her own life, and her need to seek greater fulfilment. As “the only one now”, she must find this within herself.
